\chapter{Introduction}

With technical progress in the field of robotics and related areas autonomous robots are now able to execute many tasks in factories even without modifications of the environment, like painted lines. However robots struggle to conquer everyday human environments. One reason is the much higher complexity of everyday human environments.   Factories have a relatively simple structure, . Domestic environments have a lot of variation and the structure is much more difficult to understand. The simple approach, assuming an unstructured environment, is sufficient for simple tasks like floor cleaning, but more complex tasks can benefit a lot from the usage of knowledge about the structure of domestic environments.

This thesis presents a solution for active object search in unknown indoor environments search using commonsense knowledge. Active object search is the task of finding objects using the sensors mounted on a mobile robot. 

While robots are nowadays widely used in factories there are few applications of robots in domestic environments. One big reason for this, beside the cost of course, is that in factories the environment can be adjusted to the robot and therefore can be kept as simple as possible. On the other hand everyday human environments vary a lot and are often cluttered with various different objects and obstacles. Acquiring the necessary information to execute tasks in such chaotic environments is much more complicated and therefore usually afflicted with uncertainty. One way to deal with such complicated environments and uncertain information is to make as little assumptions as possible, as no assumptions are better than wrong assumptions. For example many systems implementing SLAM (simultaneous localization and mapping) follow this approach with success. But in fact human made environments are highly structured. Most indoor environments are segmented into rooms. Each room consists of one or a few different areas with each area having a narrow range of special usages (e.g. a kitchen is used for cooking). Based on this information and further knowledge various other things can be inferred, like which objects are likely to be in a certain room. By studying human behavior one can immediately see how beneficial such commonsense knowledge about the environment can be in many tasks.

One of such is the task covered in this thesis, active object search in unknown indoor environments. The goal of this task is to find a searched object in an at the beginning unknown or partially known indoor environment. This task is very suitable for studying the impact of commonsense knowledge. One the one hand, as already mentioned, object locations correlate with various different features of the environment, making the use of commonsense knowledge highly beneficial. On the other hand to execute the task only two dimensional movement of the robot is needed. Therefore the robot setup can be kept simple and many difficult robotic tasks like grasping can be avoided. 

While most other research on this task focuses on the search of object instances this thesis is about the search of an object of a certain object class. The main difference here is the way how the object detection can be done. When searching for an object instance an object detector is trained on the searched object before executing the search. On the other hand when searching for objects of a certain class a ``general purpose'' object detector is needed as objects of the same class can look quite differently. With the increasing computational power of GPUs and the use of neural networks for computer vision tasks the performance of object detectors improved a lot. Nowadays object detectors, which are trained on thousands of images and are able to detect a reasonable number of different object types, are available. While their performance is still far from perfect their use in robotics is now viable, as this thesis will show.

The weights learned by the neural network for object detection can be seen as commonsense knowledge. To execute an object search intelligent other pieces of commonsense knowledge are needed. In this thesis the concept of rooms was heavily used. It allows the environment to be segmented into easier to handle subspaces, the rooms. Furthermore the knowledge of the room type is used to refine object probabilities in already seen areas as well as to estimate object probabilities in unexplored areas.

The system presented in this thesis puts together the commonsense knowledge mentioned above and sensor information from RGBD-cameras and a laser scanner to form a hybrid map representation consisting of a topological map of the room structure and metric semantic maps of the individual rooms. Further it is shown how this representation is used to plan an efficient search path minimizing the expected search time. The benefits of this representation and how it compares to an uninformed search using no commonsense knowledge are also covered. While there is still a long way to go to achieve human-like performance the importance of intelligent and efficient object search is clear, as it is a fundamental capability for future robots working outside factory floors and the insight about the usage of commonsense knowledge can also be applied to other tasks.

% This task is very suitable for studying the impact of using commonsense knowledge in robotics. While a simple robot setup, capable of two dimensional movement and equipped with some sensors, is sufficient, 
% 
% A suitable task to investigate the benefits of using commonsense knowledge in robotics is active object search. While being a rather simple task with little requirements for the robot hardware the positive impact of the usage of commonsense knowledge should be huge. An uninformed search policy using no commonsense knowledge can only improve the expected search time by maximizing the coverage of the views. Humans on the other hand perform much better, as they can estimate the probability of an object being somewhere based on features of the room or the area. This enables the possibility to search in likely locations first and therefore most likely save a lot of time.
% 
% When trying to implement such behavior on a robot there are three problems to solve. Firstly the commonsense knowledge to be used has to be chosen. With the current technological possibilities it is infeasible to implement a robotic system using all possible information. So the essential pieces have to be chosen. The second problem is how this information can be acquired. Humans learn a lot during their life, by processing sensed information and also by learning from other people. Neither learning from people nor the robot generating the information by itself is a reasonable approach, at least in the course of this work. So the best available information has to be selected. The last and most complex problem is how to represent the used commonsense knowledge and how to use it in the search planning. When those problems are solved the robot is able to search in an intelligent, human-like way.